Honestly I probably have the opposite opinion to you in this. This was the most enjoyable film for me out of the whole trilogy, but not because it was genuinely good, but because it was an absolute mess and it felt like they didn't even care about cohesion anymore, they didn't care about how blatant they were being about the fanservice, and watching them scramble to cram as much as they possibly could was hilarious. In the first two I had the hope of them being good, but Rei and all the other bullshit ruined it for me. In this one I was fully expecting a disaster and that's what I got. The odd dialogue, the extremely convenient plot, how borderline anime it all started to become. I liked how they pretty much stopped the pretense of Rei totally not being a Mary Sue (for the most part) and just gave her all the possible powers they could.

About her being Palpatine's granddaughter, I like the twist. I feel like it doesn't make sense because I'm pretty sure they weren't planning on it at all, just that everyone hated Ryan Johnson's twists so much that they decided to replace them with the most popular theory on Reddit instead, it was so much better than her being "aBsOlUteLy No OnE".

I think any Star Wars fan would probably be disgusted by the blatant pandering and retconning (Leia is a Jedi?? Fucking Sith cloning facilities??? What??) but the only piece of Star Wars media I truly got invested in was Clone Wars, so I was more than happy to watch the circus burn down.

snippet.textDisplay:
Bit disappointed here, IHE. Your criticism used to have more layers than that. I really liked your first two reviews on this trilogies, because you held the fanbase accountable, you weren't obsessed with your own viewpoints, you weren't afraid to swim against the loud obnoxious internet mainstream and you talked about more aspects of film making than just some creative decisions. That was very refreshing to watch, especially after TLJ came out and the Star Wars community on the internet turned into the usual hellscape as it always does when a new movie comes out. This time it just feels like part of the noise. I mean, i really didn't like Rise of Skywalker either and agree with you on some things, but I find it disappointing (and also very ironic) that in order to make this final one, you had to turn a 180° on what you said before, only to boil it down to just bitterness. So after all, your grand result is: Disney sucks? That's it? "This sucks! That sucks! I won't even bother with arguments or what transpired behind the scenes! Everything just sucks! Muh, Disney kills Star Wars." In your last video you applauded Disney for giving Rian Johnson so much creative freedom. Here you claim Disney is running everything into the ground. Sure, opinions change, but that's kind of a weird and drastic change.
You kinda saved it with your final sentence, but still... I thought you would have a lot more to say here. Like the fact that J.J. Abrams seemed to have bent over backwards in order to realize every single demand that this weird backlash has screamed throughout the internet.
"Rey can't just be noone! She has to be related to someone famous!" Boom! She's a Palpatine!
"Snoke can't just be Snoke! He has to be a Palpatine clone or something!" Boom! He's a Palpatine clone or something!
"Muh! Rey such a Mary Sue!" Boom! She's training now! Also it's okay that she's powerfull now, because she is related to a powerfull man. That makes it better, right?
(Also I don't think it's a coincedence that they put Kelly Marie Trans character in the background after she has literally been bullied into depression by angry fans.)

And the list goes on. I have never understood why people claim that TLJ ignored what came before. Even after two years, nobody was ever able to explain to me why that is. It certainly made some drastic decisions, but for all I can tell, all plot lines and character arcs from TFA have been picked up. Think about Rian Johnson what you want, but he worked closely with the story group (as shown in TLJ BTS material), he had a vision and he stood by it. I would call this artistic integrity. Unfortunately, J.J. Abrams seemed to have lacked that. TROS clearly cared more about appeasing this dumb backlash more than telling a good story. And I thought this is what you would talk about, following up on your criticism towards the fanbase from your last two videos. That this one is kinda on us. That the fanbase itself successfully ran Star Wars into the ground. Not without blame to Abrams who sold out, but also that this film should make us all stop and think about what we have let fan-culture become.

Obviously, I did not expect you to come to this same conclusion I did. But you didn't talk about anything like that, which I thought was kind of a let down.
